title: Pyrete Range - plants
description: All areas except the Hobbs Rd roadside (between road and fence - which contains some plantings). Initial plant list from 'Vascular Plants of the Bacchus Marsh Area' in the book Jack's Track Notes (with kind permission from the Friends of Werribee Gorge & Long Forest Mallee Inc.) and surveys by Chris Lindorff & Russell Best.

items.title: Eucalyptus aromaphloia
items.content_text:
Stunted "Scentbark" growing in Pyrete Range. 
Bark rough to small branches, thick, furrowed longitudinally, dark grey; branchlets salmon-coloured.
Adult leaves lanceolate, to 15 cm long, 2.5 cm wide, reticulation dense, with numerous oil glands. Inflorescences axillary, unbranched; 7-flowered.
Fruit pedicellate, hemispherical to spherical, valves 3 or 4, slightly exserted.

items.title: Caladenia pusilla
items.content_text: Tiny plant. As tall as the length of my little finger. New species record for the Pyrete Range.

items.title: Juncus flavidus
items.content_text: Keyed out to flavidus and fits FoV description. Culm dull green, 4mm diameter, 1m tall, pith with spaces. Long, loose cataphyll, straw upper and red-brown lower.

items.title: Juncus remotiflorus
items.content_text: Keyed out & fits FoV description. Pith with airholes rules out most other contenders. Culms blue-green, soft, 2.5mm diameter, ~50-70 striations not strongly raised. Primary bract continuous with culm. 60cm tall in temporary wet area in dry forest.

items.title: Acacia verniciflua s.s.
items.content_text: Confirms observation 4342 is verniciflua s.s. (common variant). Flexuouse habit, predominantly non-rostriform leaves, long-pedunculate at this time of year, glabrous penultimate branchlets.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Old, large-trunked, sprawling plant about 6m+ wide, 2m tall. Only this one plant at this location.

items.title: Acacia rostriformis
items.content_text: Two 4m+ rounded shrubs visible from the fence line of this private property. Then a dozen or so plants on the main road to the south of the property heading west. No other plants seen on Hogg Rd or Chapmans Rd.

items.title: Caladenia transitoria
items.content_text:
Solitary plants thinly scattered over this area. This plant 12cm tall.
Flowers open for only one to three days when the weather is warm.
